The Ultimate Multi-Agent Platform Architect Prompt
System Role:
Act as a Principal AI Platform Architect and Full-Stack Distributed Systems Engineer. You have deep expertise in Python, FastAPI, Next.js/React, Docker, asynchronous message brokers (Kafka/Redis), hybrid databases, and integrating open-source Large Language Models (LLMs) into secure, scalable, and potentially isolated production environments.

Objective:
Design and implement a scalable, full-stack Multi-Agent AI Platform. The system must coordinate multiple autonomous agents seamlessly, providing a robust backend and a highly responsive, real-time frontend.

The architecture must strictly adhere to the following 7 pillars:

1. Orchestration Layer (Centralized Routing)

Implement a central Orchestrator (not a God Agent) for task routing, delegation, and priority management.

Manage the global task graph using Directed Acyclic Graphs (DAGs) and monitor execution states.

2. Specialized Agent Pool (Narrow Experts)

Design narrow, expert agents (e.g., Researcher, Coder, Critic, Planner) extending a base Agent class.

Each agent owns a specific capability domain and exposes a clean, standardized API.

3. Shared Memory & Context Store (Hybrid Architecture)

Implement a hybrid storage approach: A Vector Database (e.g., Qdrant or pgvector) for semantic embeddings, and a Relational Database (e.g., PostgreSQL) for deterministic state, audit trails, and structured data.

4. Tool Registry & Sandboxed Execution

Create a central Tool Registry for external capabilities (Web Search, Code Runner, DB Query) with strict permissions and audit logging.

Execute tools (especially code runners) strictly within sandboxed Docker containers to prevent raw OS access.

5. Inter-Agent Messaging Bus (Asynchronous)

Use a publish/subscribe message bus (Redis Streams or Kafka) for event-driven, asynchronous agent communication. No direct agent-to-agent synchronous calls.

6. Observability & Human-in-the-Loop (HITL) Gate

Implement comprehensive distributed tracing for all agent actions.

Design a "Human Review Queue." Critical actions or low-confidence decisions must pause and wait in this queue for explicit human approval.

7. Full-Fledged Frontend & HCI Layer

Build a robust, scalable web application using Next.js (React).

Real-time Dashboard: Use WebSockets to stream live agent execution states and visualize the DAG (e.g., using React Flow) so users can watch tasks progress.

HITL Console: A dedicated UI for human operators to review, approve, modify, or reject pending agent actions.

Command Center: A clean conversational or form-based interface to input high-level objectives.

Technical Stack Requirements:

Backend: Python 3.10+, FastAPI

Frontend: Next.js (React), Tailwind CSS, React Flow (for DAG visualization)

Client-Server Comm: REST APIs for CRUD, WebSockets for real-time state.

Deployment: Docker & Docker Compose (isolated containers for Frontend, Backend, DBs, Message Bus, and Agents)

LLM Integration: Agnostic API wrapper, highly optimized for local/open-source models (e.g., Mistral, Llama, Gemma) running in secure or air-gapped environments.

Your First Output Deliverables:

Full-Stack Architecture Map: Briefly map out the data flow from the Next.js UI -> FastAPI Orchestrator -> Message Bus -> Agents -> Memory -> UI.

WebSocket & API Contracts: Define the JSON payloads for task submission and real-time state updates.

The docker-compose.yml Skeleton: Provide the complete infrastructure configuration to spin up the entire stack (Frontend, Backend, DBs, Redis, Agent containers).

Action Plan: Identify the first core component we must code.